<MEMO>  The Weekend Gardener  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  BEST BUY; TIME FOR TREES;    Nurseries attempting to reduce inventories are
offering discounts on trees such as photinia, pittosporum, junipers and
others. Looks for deals as much as 20 percent off trees selling from $17 or
more.; INDOORS; FORCE BLOOMS;    For indoor bouquets, cut a few branches of
almond, cherry, crabapple, forsythia, quince, spiraea and other
spring-blooming shrubs and trees. Force blooms on these branches by crushing
the ends of the stems with a hammer and placing them in warm water in a cool
area outdoors. In a week move the branches indoors to bloom.; VEGETABLES;
FIRST SEEDS;    Only a few seeds will germinate -- and they'll do that slowly
-- because the soil is still cold and damp. Sow beets, caraway, celery,
carrots, chard, leeks, lettuce, green onions, peas and radishes. Indoors start
eggplants, peppers and tomatoes as a promise to yourself that warm times are
coming.; YOUR CHECKLIST; (box) Finish pruning and spraying deciduous plants
and trees by the end of the month.; (box) Get after weeds before they become
established and take over everything. Hoe, hand pull or use an herbicide.;
(box) Plant bulbs such as gladioluses, calla and canna lilies, dahlias and
Dutch irises for summer bloom.; (box) Be alert to frost danger and protect
plants when temperatures below 32 degrees are predicted.; (box) Start seed for
summer annuals in trays or pots indoors.; (box) Although nursery stock of
bare-root fruit trees and roses is running down, you can still plant them if
you do it soon.; (box) Finish dormant pruning of dormant trees, vines shrubs
including fruit trees, roses, grapes and berries.  </TEXT>
